cause the abstract was not required at the time of proposal submission, but may be because it included sensitive information such as personal details.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>A transformative technology -imaging the activity of single neural cells deep in the
mammalian brain during behaviour via GRIN-optics in vivo microscopy (GIVM) -has recently
become available. GIVM gives a step-change in the analysis of how neurons and other cells,
such as glial cells, control behaviour and has imposed a new evidential standard for
understanding the neural basis of behaviour in mammals.
We propose to become early adopters of GIVM in the UK and apply it to three core
projects where we have made leading contributions that shape the international research
agenda. These projects ?central control of feeding, chemosensory control of breathing, and
functional connectivity within the master circadian clock ?are areas of untapped potential at
Warwick. Application of GIVM will give major advances by refuting or validating untested
assumptions, and new ways to examine neural control in each of these projects. We shall
extend the use of GIVM by: imaging activity of non-neuronal cells in the brain; combining it
with real-time measurement of neurochemicals; and simultaneously performing fluorescent
and bioluminescent detection.
After establishing GIVM in the core projects, we shall extend its application to next-phase
projects that engage other Warwick neuroscience researchers. Potential projects include:
longitudinal monitoring of how environmental enrichment alters hippocampal synaptic
connectivity and network activity; studying development of pathological patterns such as
seizure activity.
Our proposal fits fully with the MRC strategy for discovery research in neuroscience (linking
genome data and cognitive processes with behaviour and neuronal systems). By adopting
GIVM, we will be able to attain the highest standards of rigour in mammalian neuroscience.
This achievement will underpin a range of future grant applications that will build on, and
sustain, the aims of the Discovery Award, and allow wider dissemination of these methods in
the UK.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2019-02-28</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2016-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>973000</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Brain event</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>3A2A4700-6E6A-4E50-91B6-89B3168A9B1E</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Display of brain neuroanatomy, and information. Small group conversations with members of public about aspects of brain function and implications for society: e.g. how memories are stored; control of breathing; control of body weight through regulating food intake; healthy raging.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58c13b2cc1f028.86629273</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.theherbert.org/whats_on/104/amazing_brain</gtr:url><gtr:year>2017</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Science evenings</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an open day or visit at my research institution</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>31A9F343-9E7A-423B-8821-9B884E377DE4</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Initiated a series of Public Science events at the School of Life Sciences. Organised first such event on &amp;quot;A Healthy Brain for a Healthy Life&amp;quot;. About 140 members of public attended. The event involved 3 short talks (one of which delivered by me &amp;quot;The Greedy Brain&amp;quot; on how the brain controls body weight), demonstrations, and lab tours.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58